[49m[39m    1,   1[0m:[39m[49m # Recipe 15.2: Notification Timing Optimization
[0m[49m[39m    2,   2[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m    3,   3[0m:[39m[49m **Complexity:** Simple · **Phase:** MVP · **Estimated Cost:** ~$100–300/month (training + inference infrastructure)
[0m[49m[39m    4,   4[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m    5,   5[0m:[39m[49m ---
[0m[49m[39m    6,   6[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m    7,   7[0m:[39m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[39m    8,   8[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m    9,   9[0m:[39m[49m Your health system sends 50,000 medication refill reminders a month. Open rate: 12%. Your diabetes management program sends weekly educational content. Engagement rate: 8%. Your care gap outreach team sends colonoscopy screening reminders. Response rate: 4%.
[0m[49m[39m   10,  10[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   11,  11[0m:[39m[49m These aren't bad messages. The content is relevant. The patients genuinely need the information. But the messages arrive at 2pm on a Tuesday when the patient is in a meeting, or at 7am on a Saturday when they're sleeping in, or during the exact window when they're commuting and will swipe-dismiss anything that isn't a text from their spouse.
[0m[49m[39m   12,  12[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   13,  13[0m:[39m[49m Timing kills engagement in healthcare communications. And the waste isn't just operational (sending messages nobody reads costs money). It's clinical. A medication adherence reminder that arrives at the wrong moment doesn't just get ignored. It trains the patient to ignore future reminders. You're actively conditioning disengagement.
[0m[49m[39m   14,  14[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   15,  15[0m:[39m[49m The standard approach is to pick a "best" time based on population averages. Send refill reminders at 9am because that's when open rates are highest across all patients. But population averages hide enormous individual variation. The retired patient who checks their phone at 6am is fundamentally different from the night-shift nurse who's asleep until noon. The parent who has a quiet moment at 8:30pm after the kids are in bed is different from the early-riser who's unreachable after 9pm.
[0m[49m[39m   16,  16[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   17,  17[0m:[39m[49m What you actually want is a system that learns, for each patient, when they're most likely to engage with a specific type of health communication. Not just "when do they open messages" but "when do they open messages and actually take the recommended action" (refill the prescription, schedule the appointment, read the educational content).
[0m[49m[39m   18,  18[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   19,  19[0m:[39m[49m This is a textbook reinforcement learning problem. The agent observes context (patient, message type, time features), takes an action (send now, or wait), receives a reward (engagement or not), and learns a per-patient policy over time. The exploration cost is low (worst case: a message arrives at a suboptimal time and gets ignored, which is already the baseline). The reward signal is fast and unambiguous. And the improvement potential is substantial: personalized timing typically improves engagement rates by 20-40% over population-level defaults.
[0m[49m[39m   20,  20[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   21,  21[0m:[39m[49m ---
[0m[49m[39m   22,  22[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   23,  23[0m:[39m[49m ## The Technology: Reinforcement Learning for Send-Time Optimization
[0m[49m[39m   24,  24[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   25,  25[0m:[39m[49m ### Why This Is an RL Problem (Not Just Prediction)
[0m[49m[39m   26,  26[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   27,  27[0m:[39m[49m You might be thinking: "Can't I just build a classifier that predicts the best send time for each patient?" You could. But there's a subtle problem with the pure prediction approach.
[0m[49m[39m   28,  28[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   29,  29[0m:[39m[49m A classifier trained on historical data learns from the times you happened to send messages in the past. If you've always sent refill reminders at 9am, your model learns that 9am is when patients engage with refill reminders. It can't tell you whether 7pm would have been better because you never tried 7pm. This is the exploration problem, and it's exactly what RL is designed to solve.
[0m[49m[39m   30,  30[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   31,  31[0m:[39m[49m RL balances exploitation (send at the time you currently believe is best) with exploration (occasionally try different times to discover if something better exists). Over time, it converges on the true optimal timing for each patient, not just the best time among the times you've historically tried.
[0m[49m[39m   32,  32[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   33,  33[0m:[39m[49m The second reason this is RL rather than pure prediction: the reward isn't just "did they open it." It's "did they take the desired action within a reasonable window." That action might happen hours after the message was opened. The delayed, sparse reward signal is more naturally handled by RL's credit assignment mechanisms than by a simple classifier.
[0m[49m[39m   34,  34[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   35,  35[0m:[39m[49m ### The MDP Formulation
[0m[49m[39m   36,  36[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   37,  37[0m:[39m[49m **State (what the agent observes at decision time):**
[0m[49m[39m   38,  38[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   39,  39[0m:[39m[49m The state captures everything relevant to predicting engagement at this moment:
[0m[49m[39m   40,  40[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   41,  41[0m:[39m[49m - Patient features: age bucket, chronic conditions, historical engagement rate, preferred channel (SMS vs. push vs. email), days since last interaction
[0m[49m[39m   42,  42[0m:[39m[49m - Temporal features: day of week, hour of day, holiday flag, days since last message sent to this patient
[0m[49m[39m   43,  43[0m:[39m[49m - Message features: type (refill reminder, appointment reminder, educational content, care gap outreach), urgency level, length
[0m[49m[39m   44,  44[0m:[39m[49m - Contextual signals: weather (yes, really; engagement patterns shift on rainy days), local events, recent app activity if available
[0m[49m[39m   45,  45[0m:[39m[49m - Fatigue indicators: messages sent in last 7 days, messages ignored in last 7 days, current "do not disturb" window if set
[0m[49m[39m   46,  46[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   47,  47[0m:[39m[49m **Actions (what the agent decides):**
[0m[49m[39m   48,  48[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   49,  49[0m:[39m[49m The simplest formulation: the agent chooses a send-time slot from a discrete set. For example, divide the day into 30-minute windows from 7am to 9pm (28 possible slots), and the agent picks one.
[0m[49m[39m   50,  50[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   51,  51[0m:[39m[49m A slightly more sophisticated formulation: the agent decides "send now" or "defer" at each evaluation point. The system evaluates every 30 minutes whether to send a pending message. This naturally handles the case where a message becomes time-sensitive (appointment reminder for tomorrow can't wait indefinitely).
[0m[49m[39m   52,  52[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   53,  53[0m:[39m[49m For most implementations, the discrete time-slot approach is simpler and works well. The "send or defer" approach is better when messages have varying urgency and deadlines.
[0m[49m[39m   54,  54[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   55,  55[0m:[39m[49m **Reward (the signal that drives learning):**
[0m[49m[39m   56,  56[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   57,  57[0m:[39m[49m This is where healthcare notification timing gets interesting. You don't just want opens. You want actions.
[0m[49m[39m   58,  58[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   59,  59[0m:[39m[49m - +1.0: Patient takes the desired action within 24 hours (refills prescription, schedules appointment, completes survey)
[0m[49m[39m   60,  60[0m:[39m[49m - +0.3: Patient opens/reads the message but doesn't act
[0m[49m[39m   61,  61[0m:[39m[49m - 0.0: Message is ignored (no open within 48 hours)
[0m[49m[39m   62,  62[0m:[39m[49m - -0.1: Patient unsubscribes or opts out of future messages
[0m[49m[39m   63,  63[0m:[39m[49m - -0.5: Patient explicitly marks message as spam or files a complaint
[0m[49m[39m   64,  64[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   65,  65[0m:[39m[49m The asymmetry is intentional. An ignored message is neutral (the baseline). An opt-out is actively harmful because you've lost the channel entirely. A completed action is the gold standard.
[0m[49m[39m   66,  66[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   67,  67[0m:[39m[49m **Episode structure:** Each message send is one episode. State observed, action taken (time slot selected), reward received within 48 hours. No multi-step sequential decisions within a single message. This makes it a contextual bandit rather than full RL, which is a significant simplification.
[0m[49m[39m   68,  68[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   69,  69[0m:[39m[49m ### Contextual Bandits: The Right Abstraction
[0m[49m[39m   70,  70[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   71,  71[0m:[39m[49m For notification timing, a contextual bandit is almost always the right formulation rather than full RL. Here's why:
[0m[49m[39m   72,  72[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   73,  73[0m:[39m[49m In full RL, the agent reasons about how today's action affects tomorrow's state. "If I send a message today and it gets ignored, does that change the patient's likelihood of engaging tomorrow?" Theoretically yes (message fatigue is real), but modeling that multi-step dynamic adds enormous complexity for marginal benefit.
[0m[49m[39m   74,  74[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   75,  75[0m:[39m[49m In a contextual bandit, each decision is independent. The agent observes context, picks an action, gets a reward. Done. The "fatigue" effect is captured implicitly through the state features (messages sent in last 7 days, recent ignore rate) rather than through explicit multi-step planning.
[0m[49m[39m   76,  76[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   77,  77[0m:[39m[49m Contextual bandits are:
[0m[49m[39m   78,  78[0m:[39m[49m - Easier to implement (no value function estimation, no temporal difference learning)
[0m[49m[39m   79,  79[0m:[39m[49m - Easier to debug (each decision is self-contained)
[0m[49m[39m   80,  80[0m:[39m[49m - Easier to explain to stakeholders ("the system picks the best time based on patient patterns")
[0m[49m[39m   81,  81[0m:[39m[49m - Faster to converge (fewer parameters, simpler optimization)
[0m[49m[39m   82,  82[0m:[39m[49m - Nearly as effective as full RL for this problem class
[0m[49m[39m   83,  83[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   84,  84[0m:[39m[49m The main algorithms you'll encounter:
[0m[49m[39m   85,  85[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   86,  86[0m:[39m[49m **LinUCB (Linear Upper Confidence Bound):** Models the expected reward as a linear function of context features. Adds an exploration bonus proportional to uncertainty. Simple, interpretable, works well when the relationship between features and reward is approximately linear. This is the "start here" algorithm.
[0m[49m[39m   87,  87[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   88,  88[0m:[39m[49m **Thompson Sampling with neural networks:** Maintains a posterior distribution over reward predictions. Samples from the posterior to select actions. More expressive than LinUCB, handles non-linear patterns, but harder to implement correctly.
[0m[49m[39m   89,  89[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   90,  90[0m:[39m[49m **Epsilon-greedy with a learned policy:** Use the best-known time slot most of the time. Randomly explore with probability epsilon. Decrease epsilon over time. The simplest approach, but wastes exploration budget on obviously bad times.
[0m[49m[39m   91,  91[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   92,  92[0m:[39m[49m For healthcare notification timing, LinUCB or Thompson Sampling are the standard choices. LinUCB if you want interpretability and simplicity. Thompson Sampling if you want better exploration efficiency and can handle the implementation complexity.
[0m[49m[39m   93,  93[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   94,  94[0m:[39m[49m ### Offline Learning: Starting Without Exploration
[0m[49m[39m   95,  95[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   96,  96[0m:[39m[49m You don't need to explore from scratch. You have historical data: every message you've ever sent, when you sent it, and whether the patient engaged. That's enough to bootstrap a reasonable policy before any online exploration begins.
[0m[49m[39m   97,  97[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   98,  98[0m:[39m[49m The offline training process:
[0m[49m[39m   99,  99[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  100, 100[0m:[39m[49m 1. Collect historical send logs: (patient features, message features, time sent, engagement outcome)
[0m[49m[39m  101, 101[0m:[39m[49m 2. Treat the historical send time as the "action taken" and the engagement as the "reward received"
[0m[49m[39m  102, 102[0m:[39m[49m 3. Use inverse propensity scoring or doubly-robust estimation to correct for the fact that your historical policy wasn't random (you always sent at 9am, so you have lots of data for 9am and almost none for 7pm)
[0m[49m[39m  103, 103[0m:[39m[49m 4. Train the bandit model on this corrected dataset
[0m[49m[39m  104, 104[0m:[39m[49m 5. Deploy the learned policy with a small exploration rate to continue improving
[0m[49m[39m  105, 105[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  106, 106[0m:[39m[49m The key challenge with offline learning is coverage. If you've never sent messages at 10pm, you have zero data about 10pm engagement. The offline model can't learn about time slots it's never observed. This is why you need some online exploration after deployment, even if the initial policy is trained offline.
[0m[49m[39m  107, 107[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m <!-- TODO (TechWriter): Expert review ARCH-1 (HIGH). Add offline policy evaluation (OPE) subsection here: cover doubly-robust estimation for deterministic historical policies, coverage limitations, confidence intervals, and deployment gates (only deploy if OPE estimate exceeds baseline by a statistically significant margin). -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  108, 110[0m:[39m[49m ### Safety Constraints for Healthcare Notifications
[0m[49m[39m  109, 111[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  110, 112[0m:[39m[49m Even though notification timing is low-stakes compared to clinical RL, there are real constraints:
[0m[49m[39m  111, 113[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  112, 114[0m:[39m[49m **Quiet hours.** Never send between 9pm and 7am unless the patient has explicitly opted in to late notifications. This is both a regulatory consideration (TCPA for SMS) and a respect consideration. Hard constraint, not learnable.
[0m[49m[39m  113, 115[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  114, 116[0m:[39m[49m **Frequency caps.** No more than N messages per day, M per week, regardless of what the timing model suggests. If the model thinks 3pm Tuesday is optimal for three different messages, you still only send one. Priority ordering handles the rest.
[0m[49m[39m  115, 117[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  116, 118[0m:[39m[49m **Channel-specific rules.** SMS has different timing norms than push notifications. Email can arrive anytime (people check it on their schedule). Phone calls have strict TCPA windows. The model should respect channel-specific constraints.
[0m[49m[39m  117, 119[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  118, 120[0m:[39m[49m **Urgency overrides.** A medication interaction alert doesn't wait for the "optimal" time. Time-sensitive clinical notifications bypass the timing optimizer entirely. The system needs a clear priority hierarchy.
[0m[49m[39m  119, 121[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  120, 122[0m:[39m[49m **Opt-out respect.** If a patient has set "do not disturb" hours in their profile, those are absolute. The model doesn't get to override patient preferences, even if it thinks engagement would be higher.
[0m[49m[39m  121, 123[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Regulatory note:** Systems that optimize timing specifically to increase medication adherence may warrant review under FDA's Clinical Decision Support (CDS) guidance. The line between "informing" a patient and "driving" adherence behavior is genuinely ambiguous here. If your reward signal explicitly targets prescription refill completion, consult your regulatory team on CDS classification.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  122, 126[0m:[39m[49m ---
[0m[49m[39m  123, 127[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  124, 128[0m:[39m[49m ## General Architecture Pattern
[0m[49m[39m  125, 129[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  126, 130[0m:[39m[49m The system has four logical components that work together:
[0m[49m[39m  127, 131[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  128, 132[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  129, 133[0m:[39m[49m [Message Queue] → [Timing Decision Engine] → [Scheduled Delivery] → [Outcome Tracker]
[0m[49m[39m  130, 134[0m:[39m[49m        ↑                    ↑                                              |
[0m[49m[39m  131, 135[0m:[39m[49m        |                    |                                              |
[0m[49m[39m  132, 136[0m:[39m[49m   [Message Sources]    [Patient Context Store]          [Reward Signal] ←──┘
[0m[49m[39m  133, 137[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  134, 138[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  135, 139[0m:[39m[49m **Message Queue:** Upstream systems (care management, pharmacy, scheduling) generate messages that need to be sent. Instead of sending immediately, they're placed in a queue with metadata: patient ID, message type, urgency level, deadline (if any), and content.
[0m[49m[39m  136, 140[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  137, 141[0m:[39m[49m **Timing Decision Engine:** The bandit model. For each queued message, it observes the current context (patient features, temporal features, message features), selects the optimal send-time slot, and schedules delivery. For urgent messages, it bypasses optimization and sends immediately.
[0m[49m[39m  138, 142[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  139, 143[0m:[39m[49m **Scheduled Delivery:** A scheduler that fires messages at their assigned times. Handles the mechanics of channel selection (SMS, push, email), template rendering, and delivery confirmation.
[0m[49m[39m  140, 144[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  141, 145[0m:[39m[49m **Outcome Tracker:** Monitors engagement signals (opens, clicks, actions taken) and maps them back to the original send decision. Computes the reward signal and feeds it back to the model for learning.
[0m[49m[39m  142, 146[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  143, 147[0m:[39m[49m **Patient Context Store:** A feature store containing per-patient engagement history, preferences, demographic features, and derived signals (recent fatigue score, preferred time windows from historical data).
[0m[49m[39m  144, 148[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  145, 149[0m:[39m[49m The key architectural insight: the timing decision is decoupled from message generation. Upstream systems don't need to know about the optimization. They generate messages; the timing engine decides when to deliver them. This separation of concerns means you can add timing optimization to existing notification infrastructure without rewriting the message generation logic.
[0m[49m[39m  146, 150[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-message coordination:** If a patient has multiple pending messages, the timing engine must serialize decisions for the same patient. Without coordination, parallel processing can schedule three messages to the same "optimal" slot, defeating the frequency cap. Implement a per-patient scheduling lock or deduplication check at schedule creation time: before creating a new schedule, verify no other schedule exists for this patient within a 2-hour window.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  147, 153[0m:[39m[49m ---
[0m[49m[39m  148, 154[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  149, 155[0m:[39m[49m ## The AWS Implementation
[0m[49m[39m  150, 156[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  151, 157[0m:[39m[49m ### Why These Services
[0m[49m[39m  152, 158[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  153, 159[0m:[39m[49m **Amazon Personalize for the bandit model.** Personalize supports contextual bandit use cases natively through its "USER_PERSONALIZATION" recipe with exploration. It handles the exploration/exploitation tradeoff, model training, and real-time inference. You feed it interactions (message sends and engagement outcomes), and it learns per-user timing preferences. The key advantage: you don't need to implement LinUCB or Thompson Sampling yourself. Personalize handles the algorithm selection and hyperparameter tuning.
[0m[49m[39m  154, 160[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  155, 161[0m:[39m[49m **Amazon SQS for the message queue.** Messages awaiting timing decisions sit in SQS with visibility timeouts aligned to their delivery windows. SQS handles the durability, ordering, and retry semantics. Dead letter queues catch messages that fail to schedule.
[0m[49m[39m  156, 162[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  157, 163[0m:[39m[49m **Amazon DynamoDB for the patient context store.** Per-patient feature vectors need sub-millisecond reads at decision time. DynamoDB's key-value access pattern is ideal: look up patient ID, get their feature vector, pass it to the model. TTL on engagement history entries keeps the table from growing unbounded.
[0m[49m[39m  158, 164[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 159     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m **AWS Lambda for orchestration.** The timing decision is a stateless function: read message from queue, fetch patient context, call Personalize for a recommendation, schedule the delivery. Lambda's event-driven model fits perfectly. A scheduled Lambda also handles the "check for messages whose delivery window has arrived" pattern.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m <!-- TODO (TechWriter): Expert review SEC-1 (HIGH). Add guidance on PHI behavioral profiling: (1) Scope DynamoDB read access to the timing engine Lambda role only via IAM resource conditions. (2) Define explicit TTL of 90-180 days on engagement history items. (3) Note that behavioral engagement profiles derived from health communications may constitute PHI under HIPAA and should be included in the facility's Notice of Privacy Practices. (4) Implement a patient profile deletion endpoint for right-of-access requests. -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS Lambda for orchestration.** The timing decision is a stateless function: read message from queue, fetch patient context, call Personalize for a recommendation, schedule the delivery. Lambda's event-driven model fits perfectly. A scheduled Lambda also handles the "check for messages whose delivery window has arrived" pattern. Lambda security groups should restrict outbound traffic to VPC endpoints only (no internet egress). All AWS service calls in this architecture can be routed through VPC endpoints, eliminating the need for internet access entirely.
[0m[49m[39m  160, 168[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  161, 169[0m:[39m[49m **Amazon EventBridge Scheduler for timed delivery.** Once the model selects a send time, EventBridge Scheduler fires at that exact time to trigger the actual delivery. One-time schedules (not recurring) for each message. This replaces the need for a custom scheduler or cron-based polling.
[0m[49m[39m  162, 170[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 163     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m **Amazon Pinpoint for multi-channel delivery.** Pinpoint handles the actual send across SMS, push notification, and email. It also provides delivery and engagement tracking (opens, clicks) that feed back into the reward signal.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m <!-- TODO (TechWriter): Expert review ARCH-2 (HIGH). Address EventBridge Scheduler silent failure mode: (1) Add a time validation check ensuring the selected slot is in the future with a minimum 2-minute buffer; if not, send immediately. (2) SQS message deletion should happen after schedule creation confirmation, not after the timing decision. Use SQS visibility timeout extension during processing and only delete after CreateSchedule returns success. (3) Add a DLQ on the SQS queue for messages that fail scheduling after retries. -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon Pinpoint for multi-channel delivery.** Pinpoint handles the actual send across SMS, push notification, and email. It also provides delivery and engagement tracking (opens, clicks) that feed back into the reward signal. Note: Pinpoint engagement event delivery to Kinesis is a service-side integration. Pinpoint writes to the Kinesis stream using an IAM role you configure, from the AWS service network. This does not traverse your VPC.
[0m[49m[39m  164, 174[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  165, 175[0m:[39m[49m **Amazon SageMaker (alternative to Personalize).** If you need more control over the bandit algorithm (custom reward functions, specific exploration strategies, or offline policy evaluation), SageMaker lets you train and deploy custom models. More work, more flexibility. Use Personalize first; graduate to SageMaker if you hit its limitations.
[0m[49m[39m  166, 176[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  167, 177[0m:[39m[49m ### Architecture Diagram
[0m[49m[39m  168, 178[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  169, 179[0m:[39m[49m ```mermaid
[0m[49m[39m  170, 180[0m:[39m[49m flowchart TD
[0m[49m[39m  171, 181[0m:[39m[49m     A[Care Management\nPharmacy\nScheduling] -->|Generate Messages| B[SQS\nMessage Queue]
[0m[49m[39m  172, 182[0m:[39m[49m     B -->|Trigger| C[Lambda\nTiming Decision]
[0m[49m[39m  173, 183[0m:[39m[49m     C -->|Fetch Features| D[DynamoDB\nPatient Context]
[0m[49m[39m  174, 184[0m:[39m[49m     C -->|Get Recommendation| E[Amazon Personalize\nBandit Model]
[0m[49m[39m  175, 185[0m:[39m[49m     E -->|Optimal Time Slot| C
[0m[49m[39m  176, 186[0m:[39m[49m     C -->|Schedule Delivery| F[EventBridge Scheduler]
[0m[49m[39m  177, 187[0m:[39m[49m     F -->|At Scheduled Time| G[Lambda\nMessage Sender]
[0m[49m[39m  178, 188[0m:[39m[49m     G -->|Deliver| H[Amazon Pinpoint\nSMS / Push / Email]
[0m[49m[39m  179, 189[0m:[39m[49m     H -->|Engagement Events| I[Kinesis Data Stream]
[0m[49m[39m  180, 190[0m:[39m[49m     I -->|Process Outcomes| J[Lambda\nReward Calculator]
[0m[49m[39m  181, 191[0m:[39m[49m     J -->|Update Interactions| E
[0m[49m[39m  182, 192[0m:[39m[49m     J -->|Update History| D
[0m[49m[39m  183, 193[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  184, 194[0m:[39m[49m     style E fill:#ff9,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[39m  185, 195[0m:[39m[49m     style D fill:#9ff,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[39m  186, 196[0m:[39m[49m     style H fill:#f9f,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[39m  187, 197[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  188, 198[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  189, 199[0m:[39m[49m ### Prerequisites
[0m[49m[39m  190, 200[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  191, 201[0m:[39m[49m | Requirement | Details |
[0m[49m[39m  192, 202[0m:[39m[49m |-------------|---------|
[0m[49m[39m  193, 203[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Services** | Amazon Personalize, SQS, DynamoDB, Lambda, EventBridge Scheduler, Pinpoint, Kinesis Data Streams |
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 194     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m | **IAM Permissions** | `personalize:GetRecommendations`, `personalize:PutEvents`, `sqs:ReceiveMessage`, `sqs:DeleteMessage`, `dynamodb:GetItem`, `dynamodb:PutItem`, `scheduler:CreateSchedule`, `mobiletargeting:SendMessages`, `kinesis:PutRecord` |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      204[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **IAM Permissions** | `personalize:GetRecommendations`, `personalize:PutEvents`, `sqs:ReceiveMessage`, `sqs:DeleteMessage`, `dynamodb:GetItem`, `dynamodb:PutItem`, `scheduler:CreateSchedule`, `mobiletargeting:SendMessages`, `kinesis:PutRecord`. All permissions should be scoped to specific resource ARNs (queue ARN, table ARN, campaign ARN). The list above shows required actions; production IAM policies must include resource conditions. |
[0m[49m[39m  195, 205[0m:[39m[49m | **BAA** | Required. Patient contact information and engagement patterns are PHI. |
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 196     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m | **Encryption** | DynamoDB: encryption at rest (default). SQS: SSE-KMS. Kinesis: server-side encryption. S3 (training data): SSE-KMS. All transit over TLS. |
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 197     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m | **VPC** | Production: Lambda in VPC with endpoints for DynamoDB, SQS, Kinesis, and Personalize. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      206[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Encryption** | DynamoDB: encryption at rest (default). SQS: SSE-KMS with customer-managed key. Kinesis: server-side encryption with customer-managed KMS key. S3 (training data): SSE-KMS. All transit over TLS. Ensure the Kinesis stream's KMS key policy grants the Pinpoint service principal decrypt access. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      207[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **VPC** | Production: Lambda in VPC with endpoints for DynamoDB (gateway), S3 (gateway), SQS, Kinesis, Personalize, EventBridge Scheduler, Pinpoint (mobiletargeting), KMS, and CloudWatch Logs. Budget approximately $50-60/month for interface endpoints in a 3-AZ deployment. |
[0m[49m[39m  198, 208[0m:[39m[49m | **CloudTrail** | Enabled for all API calls. Pinpoint message events logged separately. |
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 199     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m | **Sample Data** | Historical message send logs with engagement outcomes. Minimum 1,000 interactions per message type for reasonable model quality. Synthetic data acceptable for development. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      209[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Sample Data** | You need at least 1,000 interactions per message type before the model learns anything useful. Synthetic data works fine for development. |
[0m[49m[39m  200, 210[0m:[39m[49m | **Cost Estimate** | Personalize: ~$0.05/1000 recommendations + training costs. SQS, Lambda, DynamoDB: negligible at typical notification volumes. Pinpoint: per-message fees (SMS ~$0.01, push free, email ~$0.0001). |
[0m[49m[39m  201, 211[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  202, 212[0m:[39m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[39m  203, 213[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  204, 214[0m:[39m[49m | AWS Service | Role |
[0m[49m[39m  205, 215[0m:[39m[49m |------------|------|
[0m[49m[39m  206, 216[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon Personalize** | Contextual bandit model for timing decisions |
[0m[49m[39m  207, 217[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon SQS** | Queues messages awaiting timing optimization |
[0m[49m[39m  208, 218[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon DynamoDB** | Stores per-patient engagement features and preferences |
[0m[49m[39m  209, 219[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Lambda** | Orchestrates timing decisions and delivery |
[0m[49m[39m  210, 220[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon EventBridge Scheduler** | Fires delivery at model-selected times |
[0m[49m[39m  211, 221[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon Pinpoint** | Multi-channel message delivery and engagement tracking |
[0m[49m[39m  212, 222[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon Kinesis Data Streams** | Streams engagement events for reward computation |
[0m[49m[39m  213, 223[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS KMS** | Encryption key management for PHI data |
[0m[49m[39m  214, 224[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon CloudWatch** | Monitoring, metrics, alarms |
[0m[49m[39m  215, 225[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  216, 226[0m:[39m[49m ### Code
[0m[49m[39m  217, 227[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  218, 228[0m:[39m[49m #### Walkthrough
[0m[49m[39m  219, 229[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  220, 230[0m:[39m[49m **Step 1: Ingest message request.** When an upstream system generates a notification (refill reminder, appointment reminder, educational content), it lands in the message queue with metadata describing the patient, message type, urgency, and deadline. Urgent messages skip the timing optimizer entirely and go straight to delivery. Everything else waits for the timing engine to decide when to send. This decoupling means upstream systems never need to know about the optimization layer. They just produce messages; the timing engine handles the rest.
[0m[49m[39m  221, 231[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  222, 232[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  223, 233[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION handle_message_request(message):
[0m[49m[39m  224, 234[0m:[39m[49m     // Check urgency first. Clinical alerts and time-critical notifications
[0m[49m[39m  225, 235[0m:[39m[49m     // bypass timing optimization entirely.
[0m[49m[39m  226, 236[0m:[39m[49m     IF message.urgency == "IMMEDIATE":
[0m[49m[39m  227, 237[0m:[39m[49m         send_now(message)
[0m[49m[39m  228, 238[0m:[39m[49m         RETURN
[0m[49m[39m  229, 239[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  230, 240[0m:[39m[49m     // Check if the message has a deadline that's already too close.
[0m[49m[39m  231, 241[0m:[39m[49m     // If the deadline is within the next decision window, send now rather than risk missing it.
[0m[49m[39m  232, 242[0m:[39m[49m     IF message.deadline AND message.deadline < (now + 1 hour):
[0m[49m[39m  233, 243[0m:[39m[49m         send_now(message)
[0m[49m[39m  234, 244[0m:[39m[49m         RETURN
[0m[49m[39m  235, 245[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  236, 246[0m:[39m[49m     // Normal path: queue the message for timing optimization.
[0m[49m[39m  237, 247[0m:[39m[49m     // Include all metadata the timing engine needs to make its decision.
[0m[49m[39m  238, 248[0m:[39m[49m     enqueue message to timing_queue with attributes:
[0m[49m[39m  239, 249[0m:[39m[49m         patient_id    = message.patient_id
[0m[49m[39m  240, 250[0m:[39m[49m         message_type  = message.type          // "refill_reminder", "appointment", "education"
[0m[49m[39m  241, 251[0m:[39m[49m         content_id    = message.content_id    // specific message template
[0m[49m[39m  242, 252[0m:[39m[49m         channel       = message.channel       // "sms", "push", "email"
[0m[49m[39m  243, 253[0m:[39m[49m         deadline      = message.deadline      // latest acceptable send time (null if no deadline)
[0m[49m[39m  244, 254[0m:[39m[49m         created_at    = current timestamp
[0m[49m[39m  245, 255[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  246, 256[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  247, 257[0m:[39m[49m **Step 2: Fetch patient context.** The timing engine needs to know about this specific patient: their historical engagement patterns, preferences, recent message history, and demographic features. This context forms the "state" that the bandit model uses to select the optimal time. The feature vector is pre-computed and stored in a fast lookup store, updated incrementally as new engagement data arrives. Without rich context, the model falls back to population-level timing, which is barely better than the static baseline.
[0m[49m[39m  248, 258[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  249, 259[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  250, 260[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION get_patient_context(patient_id):
[0m[49m[39m  251, 261[0m:[39m[49m     // Retrieve the pre-computed feature vector for this patient.
[0m[49m[39m  252, 262[0m:[39m[49m     // This includes engagement history, preferences, and derived signals.
[0m[49m[39m  253, 263[0m:[39m[49m     record = lookup from patient_context_table where key = patient_id
[0m[49m[39m  254, 264[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  255, 265[0m:[39m[49m     IF record is null:
[0m[49m[39m  256, 266[0m:[39m[49m         // New patient with no history. Return default features.
[0m[49m[39m  257, 267[0m:[39m[49m         // The model will use population-level priors until it learns this patient's patterns.
[0m[49m[39m  258, 268[0m:[39m[49m         RETURN default_context with:
[0m[49m[39m  259, 269[0m:[39m[49m             engagement_history = empty
[0m[49m[39m  260, 270[0m:[39m[49m             preferred_hours    = [9, 10, 11, 14, 15, 16]  // population defaults
[0m[49m[39m  261, 271[0m:[39m[49m             fatigue_score      = 0.0
[0m[49m[39m  262, 272[0m:[39m[49m             messages_last_7d   = 0
[0m[49m[39m  263, 273[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  264, 274[0m:[39m[49m     // Assemble the context vector the model expects.
[0m[49m[39m  265, 275[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN context with:
[0m[49m[39m  266, 276[0m:[39m[49m         historical_open_rate     = record.open_rate_30d
[0m[49m[39m  267, 277[0m:[39m[49m         historical_action_rate   = record.action_rate_30d
[0m[49m[39m  268, 278[0m:[39m[49m         preferred_hours          = record.top_engagement_hours    // learned from history
[0m[49m[39m  269, 279[0m:[39m[49m         messages_last_7d         = record.recent_message_count
[0m[49m[39m  270, 280[0m:[39m[49m         days_since_last_message  = record.days_since_last_send
[0m[49m[39m  271, 281[0m:[39m[49m         fatigue_score            = record.fatigue_score           // derived: high if many recent ignores
[0m[49m[39m  272, 282[0m:[39m[49m         age_bucket               = record.age_bucket
[0m[49m[39m  273, 283[0m:[39m[49m         chronic_conditions       = record.condition_flags
[0m[49m[39m  274, 284[0m:[39m[49m         channel_preference       = record.preferred_channel
[0m[49m[39m  275, 285[0m:[39m[49m         timezone                 = record.timezone
[0m[49m[39m  276, 286[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  277, 287[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  278, 288[0m:[39m[49m **Step 3: Select optimal send time.** This is the core decision. The bandit model takes the patient context and message features, evaluates each candidate time slot, and returns the slot with the highest expected engagement (plus an exploration bonus for uncertain slots). The model balances what it knows works for this patient with occasional exploration of new time slots. Safety constraints are applied after the model's recommendation: quiet hours are enforced, frequency caps are checked, and the selected time must fall before any message deadline.
[0m[49m[39m  279, 289[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  280, 290[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  281, 291[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION select_send_time(patient_context, message):
[0m[49m[39m  282, 292[0m:[39m[49m     // Build the feature vector combining patient context and message attributes.
[0m[49m[39m  283, 293[0m:[39m[49m     features = combine:
[0m[49m[39m  284, 294[0m:[39m[49m         patient_context                          // who they are, how they've engaged before
[0m[49m[39m  285, 295[0m:[39m[49m         message.type                             // what kind of message this is
[0m[49m[39m  286, 296[0m:[39m[49m         message.channel                          // delivery channel affects timing norms
[0m[49m[39m  287, 297[0m:[39m[49m         current_day_of_week                      // temporal context
[0m[49m[39m  288, 298[0m:[39m[49m         is_holiday_flag                          // engagement patterns shift on holidays
[0m[49m[39m  289, 299[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  290, 300[0m:[39m[49m     // Ask the bandit model for a recommended time slot.
[0m[49m[39m  291, 301[0m:[39m[49m     // The model returns a ranked list of time slots with expected reward scores.
[0m[49m[39m  292, 302[0m:[39m[49m     recommendation = call bandit_model.get_recommendation(
[0m[49m[39m  293, 303[0m:[39m[49m         user_id  = patient_context.patient_id,
[0m[49m[39m  294, 304[0m:[39m[49m         context  = features
[0m[49m[39m  295, 305[0m:[39m[49m     )
[0m[49m[39m  296, 306[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  297, 307[0m:[39m[49m     selected_slot = recommendation.top_slot     // e.g., "Tuesday 2:30pm"
[0m[49m[39m  298, 308[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  299, 309[0m:[39m[49m     // Apply safety constraints. These are hard overrides the model cannot violate.
[0m[49m[39m  300, 310[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  301, 311[0m:[39m[49m     // Constraint 1: Quiet hours (9pm - 7am in patient's timezone)
[0m[49m[39m  302, 312[0m:[39m[49m     IF selected_slot falls in quiet_hours(patient_context.timezone):
[0m[49m[39m  303, 313[0m:[39m[49m         selected_slot = next_available_slot_after(7am, recommendation.ranked_slots)
[0m[49m[39m  304, 314[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  305, 315[0m:[39m[49m     // Constraint 2: Frequency cap (no more than 2 messages per day to this patient)
[0m[49m[39m  306, 316[0m:[39m[49m     IF patient_context.messages_today >= MAX_DAILY_MESSAGES:
[0m[49m[39m  307, 317[0m:[39m[49m         selected_slot = first_slot_on_next_day(recommendation.ranked_slots)
[0m[49m[39m  308, 318[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  309, 319[0m:[39m[49m     // Constraint 3: Deadline enforcement
[0m[49m[39m  310, 320[0m:[39m[49m     IF message.deadline AND selected_slot > message.deadline:
[0m[49m[39m  311, 321[0m:[39m[49m         selected_slot = latest_valid_slot_before(message.deadline, recommendation.ranked_slots)
[0m[49m[39m  312, 322[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  313, 323[0m:[39m[49m     // Constraint 4: Channel-specific rules (SMS has TCPA windows)
[0m[49m[39m  314, 324[0m:[39m[49m     IF message.channel == "sms" AND NOT in_tcpa_window(selected_slot, patient_context.timezone):
[0m[49m[39m  315, 325[0m:[39m[49m         selected_slot = next_tcpa_valid_slot(recommendation.ranked_slots)
[0m[49m[39m  316, 326[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  317, 327[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN selected_slot
[0m[49m[39m  318, 328[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  319, 329[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  320, 330[0m:[39m[49m **Step 4: Schedule delivery.** Once the optimal time is selected, create a one-time scheduled event that will fire at exactly that time and trigger the message delivery. The schedule includes all the information needed to send the message without re-querying the timing engine. If the scheduled time is "now" (the model thinks the current moment is optimal), deliver immediately rather than creating a schedule with zero delay.
[0m[49m[39m  321, 331[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  322, 332[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  323, 333[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION schedule_delivery(message, selected_slot):
[0m[49m[39m  324, 334[0m:[39m[49m     // If the selected time is within the next 5 minutes, just send now.
[0m[49m[39m  325, 335[0m:[39m[49m     // No point creating a schedule for something that fires immediately.
[0m[49m[39m  326, 336[0m:[39m[49m     IF selected_slot <= (now + 5 minutes):
[0m[49m[39m  327, 337[0m:[39m[49m         send_message(message)
[0m[49m[39m  328, 338[0m:[39m[49m         RETURN
[0m[49m[39m  329, 339[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  330, 340[0m:[39m[49m     // Create a one-time schedule that fires at the selected time.
[0m[49m[39m  331, 341[0m:[39m[49m     create_schedule with:
[0m[49m[39m  332, 342[0m:[39m[49m         schedule_time  = selected_slot
[0m[49m[39m  333, 343[0m:[39m[49m         payload        = message                 // everything needed to send
[0m[49m[39m  334, 344[0m:[39m[49m         target         = delivery_lambda_arn     // which function to invoke
[0m[49m[39m  335, 345[0m:[39m[49m         name           = "msg-{message.id}"      // unique, for idempotency
[0m[49m[39m  336, 346[0m:[39m[49m         retry_policy   = retry 3 times with backoff
[0m[49m[39m  337, 347[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  338, 348[0m:[39m[49m     // Record the scheduling decision for later analysis and reward attribution.
[0m[49m[39m  339, 349[0m:[39m[49m     log_decision(
[0m[49m[39m  340, 350[0m:[39m[49m         message_id     = message.id,
[0m[49m[39m  341, 351[0m:[39m[49m         patient_id     = message.patient_id,
[0m[49m[39m  342, 352[0m:[39m[49m         selected_time  = selected_slot,
[0m[49m[39m  343, 353[0m:[39m[49m         model_score    = recommendation.score,
[0m[49m[39m  344, 354[0m:[39m[49m         decision_time  = now
[0m[49m[39m  345, 355[0m:[39m[49m     )
[0m[49m[39m  346, 356[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  347, 357[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  348, 358[0m:[39m[49m **Step 5: Track engagement and compute reward.** After delivery, the system monitors for engagement signals: opens, clicks, and most importantly, completed actions (prescription refilled, appointment scheduled, content read to completion). These signals arrive asynchronously, sometimes hours after delivery. The reward calculator maps engagement outcomes to numeric rewards and feeds them back to the bandit model. This closes the learning loop. Without this step, the model never improves.
[0m[49m[39m  349, 359[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  350, 360[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  351, 361[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION process_engagement_event(event):
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 352     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m     // Map the engagement event back to the original send decision.
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 353     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m     message_id = event.message_id
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 354     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m     decision   = lookup_decision(message_id)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      362[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Validate the event before processing. Verify the message_id exists in the
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      363[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // decision log and the event timestamp is within the expected reward window
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      364[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // (0-48 hours after send). Discard events that fail validation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      365[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     decision = lookup_decision(event.message_id)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      366[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF decision is null OR event.timestamp > (decision.send_time + 48 hours):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      367[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         log_invalid_event(event)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      368[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN
[0m[49m[39m  355, 369[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  356, 370[0m:[39m[49m     // Compute reward based on engagement level.
[0m[49m[39m  357, 371[0m:[39m[49m     reward = CASE event.type:
[0m[49m[39m  358, 372[0m:[39m[49m         "action_completed"  -> 1.0    // patient took the desired action (gold standard)
[0m[49m[39m  359, 373[0m:[39m[49m         "link_clicked"      -> 0.5    // engaged meaningfully but didn't complete action
[0m[49m[39m  360, 374[0m:[39m[49m         "message_opened"    -> 0.3    // opened but no further engagement
[0m[49m[39m  361, 375[0m:[39m[49m         "unsubscribed"      -> -0.5   // lost the channel entirely (very bad)
[0m[49m[39m  362, 376[0m:[39m[49m         "spam_reported"     -> -1.0   // worst outcome: regulatory risk + lost channel
[0m[49m[39m  363, 377[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  364, 378[0m:[39m[49m     // Feed the reward back to the bandit model for learning.
[0m[49m[39m  365, 379[0m:[39m[49m     record_interaction(
[0m[49m[39m  366, 380[0m:[39m[49m         user_id     = decision.patient_id,
[0m[49m[39m  367, 381[0m:[39m[49m         item_id     = decision.selected_time_slot,
[0m[49m[39m  368, 382[0m:[39m[49m         event_type  = event.type,
[0m[49m[39m  369, 383[0m:[39m[49m         reward      = reward,
[0m[49m[39m  370, 384[0m:[39m[49m         context     = decision.features,
[0m[49m[39m  371, 385[0m:[39m[49m         timestamp   = event.timestamp
[0m[49m[39m  372, 386[0m:[39m[49m     )
[0m[49m[39m  373, 387[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  374, 388[0m:[39m[49m     // Update the patient's context store with fresh engagement data.
[0m[49m[39m  375, 389[0m:[39m[49m     update_patient_context(
[0m[49m[39m  376, 390[0m:[39m[49m         patient_id  = decision.patient_id,
[0m[49m[39m  377, 391[0m:[39m[49m         last_engagement_time = event.timestamp,
[0m[49m[39m  378, 392[0m:[39m[49m         engagement_type      = event.type,
[0m[49m[39m  379, 393[0m:[39m[49m         recalculate_rates    = true    // recompute open_rate_30d, action_rate_30d, fatigue_score
[0m[49m[39m  380, 394[0m:[39m[49m     )
[0m[49m[39m  381, 395[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  382, 396[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  383, 397[0m:[39m[49m **Step 6: Handle non-engagement (timeout).** If 48 hours pass with no engagement signal, the message is considered ignored. This is the most common outcome (especially early on) and provides a neutral reward signal. The timeout handler ensures the model learns from silence, not just from positive signals. Without it, the model would only learn from engaged patients and develop a biased view of timing effectiveness.
[0m[49m[39m  384, 398[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  385, 399[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  386, 400[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION handle_engagement_timeout(message_id):
[0m[49m[39m  387, 401[0m:[39m[49m     // 48 hours have passed with no engagement signal.
[0m[49m[39m  388, 402[0m:[39m[49m     // This message was ignored. Record a neutral reward.
[0m[49m[39m  389, 403[0m:[39m[49m     decision = lookup_decision(message_id)
[0m[49m[39m  390, 404[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  391, 405[0m:[39m[49m     record_interaction(
[0m[49m[39m  392, 406[0m:[39m[49m         user_id     = decision.patient_id,
[0m[49m[39m  393, 407[0m:[39m[49m         item_id     = decision.selected_time_slot,
[0m[49m[39m  394, 408[0m:[39m[49m         event_type  = "ignored",
[0m[49m[39m  395, 409[0m:[39m[49m         reward      = 0.0,              // neutral: this is the baseline, not a failure
[0m[49m[39m  396, 410[0m:[39m[49m         context     = decision.features,
[0m[49m[39m  397, 411[0m:[39m[49m         timestamp   = now
[0m[49m[39m  398, 412[0m:[39m[49m     )
[0m[49m[39m  399, 413[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  400, 414[0m:[39m[49m     // Update fatigue indicators. Consecutive ignores increase fatigue score.
[0m[49m[39m  401, 415[0m:[39m[49m     update_patient_context(
[0m[49m[39m  402, 416[0m:[39m[49m         patient_id           = decision.patient_id,
[0m[49m[39m  403, 417[0m:[39m[49m         increment_ignore_count = true,
[0m[49m[39m  404, 418[0m:[39m[49m         recalculate_fatigue    = true
[0m[49m[39m  405, 419[0m:[39m[49m     )
[0m[49m[39m  406, 420[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  407, 421[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  408, 422[0m:[39m[49m > **Curious how this looks in Python?** The pseudocode above covers the concepts. If you'd like to see sample Python code that demonstrates these patterns using boto3, check out the [Python Example](chapter15.02-python-example). It walks through each step with inline comments and notes on what you'd need to change for a real deployment.
[0m[49m[39m  409, 423[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  410, 424[0m:[39m[49m ### Expected Results
[0m[49m[39m  411, 425[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  412, 426[0m:[39m[49m **Sample timing decision output:**
[0m[49m[39m  413, 427[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  414, 428[0m:[39m[49m ```json
